<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="193" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="193">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="193">
Verity (1923) proposed this name as a race of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. ergane" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ergane">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">P. ergane</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Geyer, 1828). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Kudrna, O" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" pagination="1 - 105" refId="B56" refString="Kudrna, O, 1983. An annotated catalogue of the butterflies named by Roger Verity. Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera 21 (1): 1 - 105" title="An annotated catalogue of the butterflies named by Roger Verity." volume="21" year="1983">Kudrna (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, this name in unavailable because it is a seasonal form and also a nomen nudum. The year on the specimen labels (1937) indicate specimens were collected 14 years after description (1923) from the same location the original holotype material was collected. As a result, the black label of the specimens treated as 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“types”">&quot;types&quot;</normalizedToken>
is erroneous. The specimen collected from the same geographical location from which the type specimen was collected is called topotype. According to ICZN (1999), a topotype has no formal standing and is not regulated by the Code. Therefore, these two specimens are erroneously labelled as types, should be annotated as &quot;Not a Type&quot; and are treated here as 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Non-type”">&quot;Non-type&quot;</normalizedToken>
specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
